##I dodged the terror cruise, but my colleagues were on it

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

The following article is from personal geography, the author of personal geography

Inspired by a journey that began in 2005 -- Harvard Press

Wang Yu, thepaper.cn

IMY doesn't know whether to count his blessings.

On February 5th, as all eyes were on the ship in Yokohama, Imy felt as if she knew she would be on it if she hadn't disembarked.

However, for some personal reasons, she finished her work early and returned home before the Spring Festival. But the Surprise, which she had stayed on a short time ago, was swallowed up by the devastation as the country's epidemic ramped up.

At the port of Yokohama on February 17, the diamond princess had been docked there for nearly two weeks. As of yesterday, the Diamond Princess confirmed the cumulative number of 454 people, many countries have begun to send a special plane to send stranded personnel back home. Omori angle, video 00:56

The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare released news on the 18th, "Diamond Princess" cruise ship personnel on the new coronavirus test results, an additional 88 people were positive. Of these, 65 had no symptoms of fever or cough. The total number of confirmed cases has increased to 562.

"This is the first cruise ship I've ever worked on, " Imy wrote in a group of friends. "I didn't expect to be introduced to my dad under these circumstances. "

Not only Imy, who would have thought that the nearly 17-year-old luxury liner is now known as the "terror cruise" . British passenger David Abel was on a cruise with his wife to celebrate their 50th wedding anniversary, and was enjoying a romance of their own; Popular Magician Chen Risheng from Taiwan was invited aboard, she and her family of seven from Hong Kong, China, set out on the first day of the Lunar New Year to celebrate the New Year at sea.

Little did anyone know, however, that when the ship sailed into the port of Yokohama, it would become a "sea prison" for 3,700 people over the next 10 days.

Unlike David and others, Imy was not a passenger, she was one of more than 1,000 employees on the diamond princess. She and her colleagues had seen countless sunrises and sunsets at sea, and knew the ship better than any guest, and the waves better than anyone. IMY's heart is heavy now as she looks at the daily "sky-high" numbers, including those of her hard-working colleagues.

There are 2,670 passengers and 1,100 crew members on the diamond princess, according to the latest figures on the ship's website. During the outbreak, the crew members also had to provide daily food delivery, towel changing, medicine delivery and cleaning services. At least 33 of the confirmed people on board are crew members, according to a Feb. 17 report on the website of the Times.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
IMY, who works on the diamond princess, escaped the disaster by returning home early for Chinese New Year. (all images in this article are provided by Imy unless otherwise specified.)

Here is IMY's dictation

(additional information in Parentheses) :

My contract wasn't due to end until February 5, but I applied early in late December because of family issues, so I didn't follow the ship to Yokohama. As a result, I seem to have been "lucky" to avoid the unexpected catastrophe, but my fellow crew members are still on board.

The diamond Princess's home port was Yokohama, which meant that most of her guests had to board the ship at the port before returning to home port to finish their journey and disembark. Each cruise company's main selling point is different. For example, parent-child themed cruise will attract family customers with children, roller coasters, water parks and other innovative facilities of the cruise more attractive to young people. Diamond Princess from the style is relatively traditional, the main star hotel services, rooms are decorated in accordance with the standards of a five-star hotel. The size of the hull is modest and medium, so it appeals to older customers and fewer young people.

(according to the diamond Princess's website, the diamond princess was built by Mitsubishi Heavy Industries in Nagasaki, Japan, on a Grand-class cruise ship registered in the United Kingdom and owned by the company, Princess Cruises, which is owned by Carnival USA.)

As a luxury liner to and from the South East Asian Airlines, the Diamond Princess has not only Chinese employees but also foreign ones, and English is the language of choice. But compared to the proportion of employees in India and the Philippines, there are not many Chinese, and only about a dozen or so people from the mainland.

(until 2014, according to public records, the diamond Princess's main routes were from Australia and New Zealand. After 2014, begin cruising Yokohama for flights to Tokyo or Kobe. Between 2016 and 2017, the diamond princess used Singapore as its home port. In December 2016, Kota Kinabalu in Malaysia and Nha Trang in Vietnam began to become one of the diamond princess'destinations. Between 2017 and 2018, the diamond princess resumed its route from Sydney, Australia. After cruising around Australia and New Zealand in 2018, the diamond princess traveled to southeast and East Asia, traveling between Japan, South Korea, Singapore, Vietnam, South East Asian Airlines and Malaysia, and is expected to continue into 2021.)

Everyone is assigned to different departments, each department's boarding time and service cycle are not quite the same. Our Department, called the art department, is mainly responsible for the ship's galleries and auctions, the work cycle is about 5 months.

On the night of February 3, a British colleague suddenly texted me, "you know what? The diamond princess is in the news! " I was surprised, and immediately worried about my colleague Erica.

Erica and I boarded the same day, and we were supposed to get off together on the last day, but I left early for personal reasons. On February 2, Erica excitedly told me that she would be off the ship in two days and asked if I wanted to meet her in Japan. Then on the night of the 3rd, after hearing that the diamond princess was on the news, Erica sent a message, saying, "maybe we won't get off the ship.

"everyone on the boat knows that a Hong Kong tourist returned to Hong Kong and was diagnosed with COVID-19 pneumonia, " Erica said.

(on February 1,2020, the Hong Kong government announced that an 80-year-old man had been diagnosed with COVID-19 pneumonia. He had boarded the diamond princess in Yokohama, Japan, on January 20 and landed in Kai Tak Cruise Terminal, Hong Kong, on January 25. On January 30, the man developed fever.)

On Feb. 4, the ship sailed into Yokohama's home port, where guests were scheduled to disembark early in the morning, but not only my colleagues, but also the passengers.

(Japan's Asahi Shimbun newspaper reported that on the night of February 3, the "Diamond Princess" arrived at Dahei Quay, Yokohama Port, without landing. On the same night, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare began quarantine work on the ship's crew of about 3,700 people. When the ship landed on February 4, Yokohama said all passengers would be delayed until after the 5 th. There were 2,666 passengers and 1,100 crew on board, according to the company's website.)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The diamond princess was moored in the harbor at night

At the end of December, when I was on the ship, we had no idea what COVID-19 pneumonia was, so people didn't seem to care much if they had a fever or a cough. And Internet access is expensive on ships, and companies charge different rates, like the Diamond Princess, which is about three hundred Renminbi, or hundreds of megabytes. Even if I buy traffic, I never want to use it on social media like Weibo. I don't want to look at my phone when I'm tired from work.

(according to the diamond Princess's website, the ship has Wi-Fi and an Internet cafe. But 120 minutes of Internet access costs $62.95(20 extra minutes if you buy the package) and $82.95(40 extra minutes if you buy the package) 

For four months at sea, I was almost cut off from the world.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Life on board had a quiet "cloistered" quality

When I learned of the outbreak, I was particularly anxious in the first few days. My biggest concern was poor communication. The diamond princess is owned by the American Carnival Group, and any questions are emailed to the head office and then wait for the head office to make a decision. Japan and the United States have a time difference of more than ten hours, communication is not smooth.
In addition, the crew was already small in number of Chinese, and Chinese employees were able to see information about various aspects of the epidemic in their circle of friends, but most of the foreign employees from the Philippines and India had little knowledge of the epidemic, many people don't take the epidemic seriously.

I was particularly impressed on the morning of February 5 when I contacted two of my Chinese colleagues on the ship to ask them about their situation. A Guy who works in a gym told me that he wasn't sure what was going on, and that people were still eating together in the staff dining room, even if they were given masks, not everyone would be wearing them.

As a bystander, I read all kinds of news about the epidemic every day in China. I see the number of people diagnosed on the diamond princess every day. I don't understand why there isn't a little bit of tension on the ship? I was even more anxious than they were, more anxious than they were for every moment of change. Until a colleague in Italy said to me, "There's no way to escape. "

Space on the ship is very closed, especially the staff quarters are basically no windows, the area is very small. Most are double rooms, a few are single rooms, since the beginning of the epidemic, no one to staff quarters disinfection, everyone after work still gathered in the staff quarters together for dinner.

In this case, it seems, as my Italian colleague put it, "there is no escaping it" . So the only way to do that is to be happy and relaxed.

In addition, unlike passengers, during the quarantine period, the ship's staff has its own work, such as patrol, on duty, food delivery, but also some cleaning work.

(according to the Asahi Shimbun, a "14-day quarantine" announcement was broadcast from the ship at around 8:10 am on February 5. The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare announced that 10 new cases of COVID-19 had been confirmed on board the ship, and that the 10 people had been taken off the ship and sent to medical facilities for treatment. A total of 273 people who had close contact with the ship were also tested for fever, cough and other symptoms.)

As of February 7, there seemed to be a slight wrinkle, with the cumulative number of confirmed cases on the ship reaching 61. Some colleagues said they had received their assigned thermometers, but others said they had not and that no one had examined them. Male colleagues at the gym told me that some people had a fever and reported it as untreated. All kinds of information, you can feel the cabin is a relatively chaotic state.

(according to the Asahi Shimbun, on February 7, Ministry of Health and Welfare announced 41 new cases, 35 of them aged over 60, bringing the total number of confirmed cases on board to 61, with about 40 members of the self-defense forces taking part in support work. Four people were taken to hospital in Shizuoka Prefecture.)

Erica told me she suspected she was infected. She says she has to deal with passengers who test positive every day, even though she has only the symptoms of a cold. I asked her why? She said that there was no one else to help, that all the work on the ship was still done by the crew, and that passengers could not leave the room but had to call the front desk to make demands, such as buying things, communicating with people, and so on, the front desk is flooded with calls every day, and everyone is going crazy. With a large number of confirmed passengers and a small Japanese speaking crew, Erica was temporarily assigned from the art department to assist with the transport of confirmed patients.

However, there were no other protective gear on board, other than a face mask. Erica only wore a mask and didn't have goggles every time she came face to face with a patient. After reporting the symptoms to the supervisor, Erica was given the opportunity to be examined out of consideration for the fact that she was in close contact.

The Room of our staff dormitory is very small, only about four or five square meters. The allocation of dormitories is tied to the level of the Staff, such as a single room if you're an Officer, a double room if you're a Staff, and a double room if you're a Crew, but both rooms share a bathroom. All staff accommodation floors are below level.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
IMY's Staff level room is a double room.

While waiting for the results, Erica was not quarantined, was still sharing a double room with a roommate, and was still eating in the staff cafeteria. This surprised and mystified me.

(according to the Asahi Shimbun, the cumulative number of confirmed cases was 70 on Feb. 9; 439 were tested on Feb. 11, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 135; four of the additional 65 were sent to hospitals in Tokyo and Kanagawa Prefecture; and 39 were confirmed on Feb. 12, including a quarantine official.)

In fact, the ship, for the staff of the hygiene requirements are very strict, such as food can not be taken outside the restaurant area. In addition to the daily personal cleaning, about every other week or so, there will be someone to check the hygiene of the staff dormitory. In addition, once employees find themselves sick, they must be the first time to report, not to report the words will be punished, according to the condition of the quarantine measures.

I remember one time I had a fever. I was quarantined in the infirmary for two days. I was allowed to go out only after repeated temperature checks to ensure that the fever was gone and that I did not have to repeat it.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the isolation ward, all meals will be delivered to the room

This time, however, the passengers and crew did not seem to be prepared for the COVID-19 outbreak, and the worrying thing is still happening.

I think the main problem is the limited space on the ship, because most of the time, passengers and crew have to share a space, like before the outbreak, at lunch time every day, passengers would gather in the 14th floor cafeteria for dinner, and then go to the theater to watch shows during the evening entertainment.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Before the outbreak, passengers would go to the theater to watch a show every night during entertainment hours

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Crew Bar

Except for open spaces such as outdoor decks, most of the activity spaces are enclosed, which naturally makes it easier for viruses to spread. Although the toilets and restaurants, etc. , placed disinfectant alcohol, hand sanitizer and other supplies, but in the theater, galleries, shops and other venues, these things are not. In addition, the stairs up and down the handrails, elevator buttons and other details, it is difficult to fully control.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
There will be a lively Samba performance on the outdoor deck

As far as I know, there were more than 2,600 passengers on the diamond princess and more than 1,000 employees on board, but there were only two doctors and several nurses in the infirmary, and the total number of staff was no more than 10. The whole clinic has a front desk, a diagnostic room, and 2 ~ 3 rooms as isolation rooms, each isolation room has 2 ~ 3 beds.

The ship's medical staff to implement shift system, work pressure is very large, and medical capacity is very limited, can only be injected, take medicine, handle more common minor problems. If a guest has a serious illness, we usually choose to contact the nearest port as soon as possible to take the patient to the local hospital.

So in the face of this COVID-19, for the ship's medical staff, it's not just that we're understaffed, it's that we may not be able to resist at all.

On Feb. 13, a handful of critically ill patients were allowed off the ship for treatment at a local hospital, and the American head office of the Diamond Princess posted a letter on Facebook, all crew members on the ship will be given one to two months'paid leave, and all expenses incurred on board during the isolation period will be reimbursed by the ship as compensation to the crew.

I don't know if there are any laws or contracts that require the crew to continue working, but in that case, I'm sure we all felt a sense of duty and obligation to serve.

(on Feb. 13,44 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 218, the Asahi Shimbun reported. There are still about 200 elderly people over 80 years old on the ship, the Health Ministry plans to let some of them off the ship first; 14,11 passengers off the ship, and arranged for quarantine observation in a school building in Saitama Prefecture and Guangshi; 15, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare said that the ship to test the entire crew, if no infection, observation period ended after 19 can be off; 16,70 new confirmed cases, of which 38 without fever and cough symptoms.)

When the crew will be able to disembark, however, remains to be seen. Now, of the five people our department left on the ship, three are sick, in quarantine, and awaiting word on their return home.

(according to the Asahi Shimbun, an American evacuation plane left Tokyo International Airport on Feb. 17, carrying 328 American citizens and their families. It is understood that after returning to the United States, they will also be in the United States military base for 14 days of quarantine inspection. Hong Kong, Australia, Canada and South Korea have also announced that they will send special planes to pick up the stranded people. As of February 17, Japan's Ministry of Health announced that the diamond princess on the cumulative number of confirmed confirmed 454 people, Japan's domestic cumulative number of confirmed 520 people.

According to the Philippine News Site Rappler on February 17 reported that the diamond princess has been diagnosed in the Philippines, 27 Filipinos, and are all crew members. The University of the Philippines in Japan said it was consulting with relevant agencies of the two governments and World Health Organization officials to ensure the health of the 538 Filipino patients on board and to assist them in returning to the Philippines.)
